Recommended Structure for Every PowerPoint

Use the same format for every deck so the whole program feels consistent and professional.

Each deck should include:

1. Purpose

Explain what the training teaches and why the team cares.

Example:

This training explains how GitLab pipelines work, how our team uses them, and how to troubleshoot common pipeline failures.

2. Where This Fits

Explain how the topic connects to the team’s real work.

Example:

This matters because pipeline failures can block releases, break automation workflows, and delay promotion between environments.

3. Core Concepts

Explain the key ideas in simple terms.

4. Team-Relevant Examples

Use sanitized examples from the team’s actual work.

5. Common Mistakes

Show what new people or busy engineers commonly get wrong.

6. Demo or Walkthrough

Include commands, screenshots, diagrams, or a process walkthrough.

7. Troubleshooting Checklist

Give people a repeatable way to approach problems.

8. Hands-On Lab

Include at least one small exercise when possible.

9. Knowledge Check

Add 3–5 questions or discussion prompts.

10. References

Link to approved internal docs, vendor docs, team runbooks, or related trainings.

11. Follow-Up Actions

Tell the learner what they should do next.

Example:

* Review the related runbook.
* Complete the lab.
* Shadow a pipeline troubleshooting session.
* Open a merge request using the standard workflow.

