You’re right — use no /srv paths. Since your runner is rootless and managed with systemctl --user, the best placement is under the runner user’s home directory.

Use this pattern:

Runner-owned fixture root:
  ~/.local/share/aerolit-molecule
Runner config:
  ~/.config/gitlab-runner/config.toml
Runner service:
  systemctl --user restart gitlab-runner
Compliance center:
  templates/ansible-molecule/*

The GitLab Runner config.toml volume mount is the key because the GitLab Docker executor uses that config to mount host paths into job containers. GitLab documents runner behavior as being controlled through config.toml, including Docker executor configuration.   Molecule’s Podman example also lines up with what you’re doing because it uses standard Ansible inventory/playbooks to control the test environment.  

⸻

Phase 1 — Create the runner-owned fixture area

Run this on the runner host as your runner user, not inside a CI job container:

export AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT="$HOME/.local/share/aerolit-molecule"
mkdir -p "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT"/{hubs,files,repos,logs,cache}
mkdir -p "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/files/current"
mkdir -p "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/repos/current"
echo "fixture-ok" > "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/files/current/.fixture-ok"
echo "fixture-ok" > "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/repos/current/.fixture-ok"
realpath "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT"
ls -la "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT"

You want the real path to look something like:

/home/YOUR_USER/.local/share/aerolit-molecule

Do not use $HOME inside config.toml. Use the actual absolute path.

⸻

Phase 2 — Create the first pinned hub snapshot

Still on the runner host:

export AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT="$HOME/.local/share/aerolit-molecule"
export SNAP_NAME="approved-$(date +%Y%m%d)"
export SNAP_DIR="$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/hubs/$SNAP_NAME"
mkdir -p "$SNAP_DIR"/{roles,collections}
cat > "$SNAP_DIR/metadata.yml" <<EOF
name: $SNAP_NAME
created_by: $(whoami)
created_at: $(date -Is)
purpose: Pinned AeroLIT Molecule dependency hub snapshot
EOF
ln -sfn "$SNAP_DIR" "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/hubs/current"
ls -la "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/hubs"
ls -la "$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/hubs/current"

For now, the hub can be mostly empty. The first goal is proving the path works.

Later it should look like this:

~/.local/share/aerolit-molecule/
├── hubs/
│   ├── approved-20260616/
│   │   ├── roles/
│   │   │   ├── administration/
│   │   │   │   └── some-required-role/
│   │   │   └── common/
│   │   │       └── repo-client/
│   │   ├── collections/
│   │   └── metadata.yml
│   └── current -> approved-20260616
├── files/
│   └── current/
├── repos/
│   └── current/
├── logs/
└── cache/

⸻

Phase 3 — Update your rootless runner config

Open:

vi ~/.config/gitlab-runner/config.toml

Find your [runners.docker] section and add a volume for the fixture root.

Example using a real absolute path:

volumes = [
  "/cache",
  "/run/user/2271030/podman/podman.sock:/run/docker.sock",
  "/run/user/2271030/podman/podman.sock:/var/run/docker.sock",
  "/home/YOUR_USER/.local/share/aerolit-molecule:/home/YOUR_USER/.local/share/aerolit-molecule:ro"
]

Keep your existing socket volumes. Just add the fixture mount.

Also add this near the [[runners]] level if you do not already have an environment entry:

environment = [
  "AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT=/home/YOUR_USER/.local/share/aerolit-molecule"
]

If you already have an environment = [...] list, append the new value instead of creating a second one.

Then restart your rootless runner:

systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user restart gitlab-runner
systemctl --user status gitlab-runner --no-pager

The important detail: the fixture path should be mounted into the job container at the same absolute path that exists on the runner host.

That matters because Molecule creates sibling UBI containers through the Podman socket. So this path:

/home/YOUR_USER/.local/share/aerolit-molecule

needs to be valid from the host Podman point of view and visible inside the CI job container.

⸻

Phase 4 — Add compliance-center variables safely

In your templates/ansible-molecule/template.yml, add an input like this:

aerolit_fixture_root:
  type: string
  default: ""

Then in the job variables, do not overwrite the real runner variable directly. Use an input variable:

variables:
  AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT_INPUT: "$[[ inputs.aerolit_fixture_root ]]"

Then in your script section, add:

# Prefer explicit component input if provided.
# Otherwise use the runner-level AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT environment variable.
if [ -n "${AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT_INPUT:-}" ]; then
  export AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT="$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT_INPUT"
fi
: "${AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT:?AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT is not set. Set it on the runner or pass aerolit_fixture_root to the component.}"
export AEROLIT_COLLECTION_HUB="${AEROLIT_COLLECTION_HUB:-$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/hubs/current}"
export AEROLIT_TEST_FILES_DIR="${AEROLIT_TEST_FILES_DIR:-$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/files/current}"
export AEROLIT_TEST_REPOS_DIR="${AEROLIT_TEST_REPOS_DIR:-$AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT/repos/current}"

This makes the compliance component portable:

Your runner:
  gets AEROLIT_FIXTURE_ROOT from config.toml
Another program:
  can pass aerolit_fixture_root as a component input

⸻

